SIMPLE: impersonal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impersonal
<hw>Im*per"son*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>impersonalis</ets>; pref. <ets>im-</ets> not +
<ets>personalis</ets> personal: cf. F. <ets>impersonnel</ets>. See
<er>Personal</er>.]</ety> <def>Not personal; not representing a person;
not having personality.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An almighty but <qex>impersonal</qex> power, called Fate.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir J. Stephen.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Impersonal verb</b></col> <fld>(Gram.)</fld>, <cd>a verb
used with an indeterminate subject, commonly, in English, with the
impersonal pronoun <xex>it</xex>; as, <xex>it rains</xex>; <xex>it
snows</xex>; <xex>methinks</xex> (it seems to me). Many verbs which are
not strictly impersonal are often used impersonally; as, <xex>it
goes</xex> well with him.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impersonal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Impersonal
<hw>Im*per"son*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which wants
personality;</def> <specif>specifically</specif> <fld>(Gram.)</fld>,
<def>an impersonal verb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impersonality</ent>⟦br⟧
